description:
The Horizon Europe-funded project FAiR (Finding Agreement in Return) aims to generate new insights into migration governance, in particular into the factors and processes that foster or impede the legitimacy and effectiveness of Europe&rsquo;s intergovernmental return and alternatives to return policies. To this purpose, consortium partners will conduct fieldwork in 5 non-EU+ countries (Georgia, Iraq, Niger, Nigeria, and Turkey) and in 10-12 EU+ countries (Germany, Italy, Poland, Switzerland, Austria, France, Sweden, the Netherlands, the United Kingdom, Spain, and Greece). The project will use qualitative and quantitative methods, including interviews, focus groups, observations, discourse and document analysis, regression analysis, and survey experiments.&nbsp; 
 By bringing together stakeholders in the EU+ and non-EU+ countries, FAiR will develop an index to measure Europe&rsquo;s return policies (MIREX); a survey experiment on public support for alternatives to return policies; guidelines to improve the human rights monitoring of enforced return and a negotiation game to help reach agreement on return.&nbsp; 
 The present methodological protocol outlines guidelines and sets the foundations for partners to: 1) collaborate by sharing existing public or shareable data, 2) coordinate fieldwork, both within and outside Europe, amongst partners collecting data from the same target group and countries and, 3) coordinate the production of outputs with common themes. This protocol also outlines some initial points for collaboration with sister consortia following discussions with GAPs and MORE. Additionally, the protocol includes a list of internal deliverable deadlines, recognizing that certain outputs are crucial for advancing the work of different tasks. It also incorporates project management practices to facilitate the coordination of the project&nbsp; and the implementation of the present protocol. 
  This deliverable is due on Month 6 of the project (31st of October 2023) and was reviewed on the 15th of November 2024 following recommendations from the European Commission and external reviewers.

